The side of the flap that has the peg sticking up should be facing the input side of the vent case.

Desk Lamp based on links.
Add as many Links as you want.
All hardware can be found at Home Depot or on Amazon and requires only simple wiring.

Supplies
1X-Button Turn Knob Socket (#100356978-Home Depot) (Leviton 4155-51-Amazon)
1X-E26 to E12 socket adapter
1X-E12 LED Bulb
1X-Power cord (any old power cord can be used)
1/4 threaded rod (length depends on how many links are used 2 1/4" per connection)
1/4 Nuts (2X per connection)
1/4 washers(4X per connection)

The Lamp Links, Lamp Base, and Shade Extender require no support when printing.
The Lamp Shade Itself will require support only from the build plate to support the link.

I designed this to be as easy to print as possible for a desk lamp with only simple wiring without soldering connections.
The Links require 4X washers because two go inside the Link on the high friction areas preventing plastic on plastic contact, and two washers on the exterior.
The Lamp socket simply passes up through the shade into a hole in the back of the Shade and has a nut included to hold it in place.
I downsized the socket size with the adapter simply to allow fitment of a smaller bulb using the smaller size thread.
The LED bulb I used was a Globe shaped bulb E-12 size made by GE (only LED bulbs should be used to reduce the chance of melting the plastic of the lamp.)
The power cord can be bought or reused from something else simply cut and strip the wires and attach them to the socket. I used an old printer power cable.

Not all parts are properly orientated in the stl files, use your own discretion.

I printed all the parts with 3 perimeters with a .4mm nozzle, and used 20% infill

The prints are a little long but in the end you have a fully functional desk lamp.

Happy Printing

description.text:
Often when I'm working on my Festool MFT workbench I'd like to be able to block some of the holes. This 'thing' lets me make as many plugs as I need.

It's also handy as a way to secure a piece of craft paper to the work surface. Just put a corner of the paper into the hole and push the plug into it.

I put some notches under the top to ease pulling it up from the surface when it's plugged in tight.

You may want to print it with a reduction of a percent or so. On my printer using 99.5% gives a clean fit with no binding. Dropping to 99% leaves enough room for heavy craft paper without having to push it up from below to release it.

I've included the Tinkercad source zip. Use that if you want to import it back into Tinkercad. It'd be easy to use that to change the logo/lettering to whatever you'd like. That or make it taller, shorter, or whatever!

description.text:
These pulleys interface to a #10 Ball/Bead chain with 4.5mm beads with approximately 5.5mm pitch.

The larger puller has 20 bead-holes evenly spaced around it's interfacing circumference and is around 34mm in diameter (not including guides). DISCLAIMER / WARNING
This is not a climbing tool! Don't use in any situation where loss of grip would cause harm to people or property.
DISCLAIMER / WARNING

This design is something that allows to quickly grip a thin rope and pull it tightly without hurting your hands.
It features a opposing rows of one-way gripping teeth so that the harder you pull, the harder it bites into and grips the rope.

To release the rope, the handle can be tilted forward while under tension, and the rope will slide out of the teeth. Alternatively you can sort of "peel" the rope back by starting at the top of the handle and pulling down to the base.

Its important to pay attention to the angle of the handle during use, so as not to inadvertently let the rope go.

I am considering adding some kind of guard at the top of the handle that would keep the rope from slipping out, but haven't decided on a solution that I like yet. As it is, you don't need access to any free end of the rope for use. Adding something like a loop on the top would mean that you restrict that ability, so I'm still thinking about it.

I designed this to work with some 750lb-test paracord that I bought online. I think the more common size of paracord is 550lb test, which might be slightly smaller diameter, though I expect it would also work fine with the same part.

The original idea behind this was for use with a pulley block and tackle setup, for hoisting heavy objects etc.

The part is completely customizable in OpenSCAD for different rope sizes, different hand sizes, etc.

To customize the part for another rope size, just measure the un-squished rope diameter "ropeD", and the diameter while squished as much as you can, with calipers "ropeFlatD".

description.text:
This is a just a fun little desk toy representation of the curve on which a square can roll smoothly, inspired by Vsauce's explanation of it in his video on brachistochrones (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=skvnj67YGmw) and Devin Montes from Make Anything's use of 3D printing to represent the tautochrone (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dIip9yXK8-M) (both of which are really awesome and you should check them out!). Traditionally, you don't think of square wheels as being capable of turning smoothly and traveling only in a horizontal line. Similarly, we don't think of a non-flat road as being able to be driven across smoothly and traveling only in a horizontal line. The very specific geometries utilized in this toy, however, make both things possible. This toy also allows you to actually see and feel the squares turning, making it far more fascinating and a more visually interesting demonstration of the principle than just looking at an animation. A fun and easy print, this desk toy will certainly make people stop and look twice!

While this is definitely able and ready to be printed right now (and I encourage you to do so), it is still a work in progress and you can expect files to change somewhat in the near future. I have not actually got around to printing this on my own printer just yet, so there may be some small tolerance adjustments that need to be made that I won't know about until I print it. If you do print it, please share and please send me feedback so I can make the changes you think are needed! I have also attached the multi-body Solidworks part file that I designed everything in (as well as a STEP file for anyone without Solidworks), so please feel free to make changes and share your improvements on my design. Just let me know if you have any questions or problems.

Thanks!

Notes:

Just print the specified amount of each of the pieces!

Base - x1
Connector - x2
Crank - x1
End Gear - x2
Handle - x1 (technically optional, although I highly recommend you print it because it allows you to turn the shaft without having to turn your grip)
Middle Gear -x1
Pin - x2
Square - x2
Wall - x2

Assembly

Once you've printed all the parts out you should be ready to assembly them (although you may have to do some sanding first if your tolerances are too tight). Assembly is fairly straightforward and you should be able to figure out what goes where based on the pictures, but just in case it isn't, here's a quick guide to make your life easier!

  1. Put the two Pin pieces and the Shaft through the holes of one of the Connectors.
  2. Slide one Square piece onto each of the Pins until it is flat against the Connector (you may want to use some glue to secure the Squares onto the Pins if your tolerances are too loose).
  3. Slide the second Connector onto the two Pins until it is against the Squares.
  4. Slide the two Walls onto the Pins and Shaft on either end until they are flat against the Connectors on opposite sides.
  5. Insert the pegs on the Walls into the holes in the Base piece.
  6. Slide the Middle Gear onto the straight end of the Shaft on the outside of the Wall.
  7. Slide an End Gear onto the long ends of each of the Pins on the outside of the Wall (again, you may want to use some glue here if these are loose), ensuring that the teeth line up with the Middle Gear and that the Squares sit properly.
  8. Slide the Handle onto the opposite end of the Shaft.
  9. Start turning and enjoy the satisfaction.

title: Big & Long Filament Spool Sprocket (Quick Change)

description.text:
Update: 2/5/17 For those that like it big and long, there is a new "stl" file that should satisfy your needs. It measures 140mm instead of the original 100mm.

This is the big version of my other part: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2067525

This spool sprocket is intended to make removing a spool of filament super easy, as easy as changing tires in NASCAR competitions, (I wish). No really, it makes removing nuts a thing of the past. It works with standard 608ZZ bearings or without, your choice. See my spool holder as this is a perfect complement to that holder but it works just as well with most other standard spool holders. (My bearings were a nice tight fit. Use the power of muscle persuasion or maybe a shop vice in a worst case scenario.)

Visit http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2009565 for my top mounted spool holder.

Changing the filament is five EASY Steps:

  1. Remove nut(s) from one side of the spool threaded rod and insert the "Spooler Bolt." Fasten the nut(s) back on. You will never need to remove nuts again! I use 2 nuts on each side to lock them into place.
  2. Place your desired spool of filament, (with filament unlike mine) in place. The rod and spool can both lay on their side.
  3. Drop the "Spooler Nut" into place.
  4. Spin tighten the "Spooler Nut" onto the "Spooler Bolt." Because I used a minimal number of threads on the nut, it spins as easy as a butterfly nut. This makes tightening the nut, a real cinch. Hand tighten the nut and bolt to finish clamping the spool into place.
  5. Mount your "Spool Sprocket" on your printer's spool holder and center it.
    Done!

To remove a spool reverse the steps above but skip step one. You're now qualified as a NASCAR technician. Now go change some tires!... I mean spools!

This spool sprocket should work for many types of filament spools. If it doesn't work for you, let me know in the comments and I'll see if I can accommodate your needs.

NOTE: This spool sprocket can handle a spool with a 105mm opening and 102mm wide. I implemented those dimension to suite someone else's request. I have not printed this out myself. My pictures are of the smaller spool sprocket. (See picture of Step 5 for dimensions of this thing.)

There is a second bolt that will handle spools 140mm wide.

This is a simple iPad-3 mount for a regular tripod. It contains 6 things, requires 2 pieces of aluminum bar 1/2" x 1/8" (about 12.8mm x 3.2mm), one M3x16mm screw and one M6x12mm hex bolt.

Print 2 copies of side.stl and decide whether you want to use top.stl, or top2.stl thing (no need to print both). The difference between these 2 files is - top.stl is designed for precisely cut bar, which will end inside the thing. When you need to install, or remove iPad, top.stl thing has to be removed from the bar and then replaced. top2.stl allows the bar to be longer and pass through it. In this case you just slide top2.stl thing along the bar, to lock/release the iPad.

Printer:

VERTEX K8400 with E3D print-heads

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.3mm

Infill:

25%

Cut 2 aluminium bars. The length of the shorter bar should be 176mm. The length of the longer bar depends on whether you will print top, or top2 thing. For top the bar length is 250mm, for top2 - 300mm. Assemble all the things; pay special attention to the orientation of the center thing and the distances between the things (see drawings). Make sure everything, including iPad, fits. Now you need to drill the holes in both bars for M3x16mm screw that will tight them together with the center thing.

Drill 3.5mm hole in the center of the shorter bar. Measure 126mm from the end of the long bar and drill 3.5mm hole there. The holes are wider than the screw; the screw should easily pass through them; it will hold on the thread cut in plastic.

Put together the bars and the center thing and fix them in this position with the screw. Glue side things to the both ends on the short bar. Make sure the distances are correct before the glue dries.
Glue the bottom thing to the same end of the long bar from where you measured 126mm when marking the spot for the hole. Make sure the distance is correct before the glue dries.

Glue M6 bolt to the bottom of the hex hole in knob thing. When the glue is completely dry screw the knob bolt into the hole in the top piece to make the thread. Place the top thing with the knob on the open end of the long bar and tighten the knob.

description.text:
This is a remix of spauda01's D-Bot XY carriage.

The front carriage plate was modified to attach E3D's Titan extruder for maximum utilization of print bed area. The Titan can be attached using the long bolts that come with the kit, provided a 2mm spacer is used between the motor and extruder. Also included is a holder for a 12mm bed leveling sensor. This design approach accommodates any size extruder motor.

The back carriage plate was modified to accommodate the original cable holder for the print head and to move it away from the extruder on the front.

Also included is a cooling duct that uses the same 40x40mm fan, but provides air to two sides of the part being printed. The cooling duct uses the same attachment method as the original duct. The redesign of the cooling duct was primarily done to provide clearance on the right side of the print head when doing the bed leveling. The cooling duct will need to be printed with supports, with best results by placing the fan attachment face on the print bed.

Move the front cross bar on the D-Bot down by about 50mm to provide clearance for the print head motor if needed.

title: Prusa i3 MK2 - Y-Frame Assembly Helper - In Quarters - Remix

description.text:
Update 03.18.2017: I just received my printer which turns out to be a mk2s. I am on chapter 2, Y-Axis. I have used my print of the Y-Frame Assemby Helper. See photo. I think it was very handy.

mdkendall's mod is a great mod. My problem with it though is metric screws are somewhat expensive and hard to come by where I live. Since this thing is likely one use, I hate to lose inserts, assuming I even have the correctly sized ones. So I altered mdkendall's remix to add a 3D printed fastener. The idea is to have a nice tight fit and then glue this thing in place using super glue. Depending on the nozzle size on your printer and how well it is tuned, the gap required could vary. I included 0.15 mm to -0.05mm sized fasteners. So if it is a little too tight or loose, just pick the next appropriately sized fastener and print it again. In my case, 0.00mm was perfect. It fits together and holds together all by itself. I will glue it though. I haven't taken a picture of it yet but it printed perfectly.

I included a step file with the 0.00mm gap. My design files are on Onshape and they are here:
https://cad.onshape.com/documents/91c028de3c2e52c4b577fe7a/w/9ae30981f084b34a98dbcba3/e/b9c23bc35b7a2be5939fd6eb

There is a variable defined for the gap size (see picture) if the included sizes don't work out, just change it to whatever you need and export out the fastener as an stl. If you don't want to do that, you can scale the fastener stl in x and y only to the appropriate size. The A and B parts should remain the same size always.

As mdkendall says, print two A and two B parts.

My mk2 won't be here for quite a while yet but I want to be ready with helpers and upgrades for when it does. I am printed mine in PLA on a Lulzbot mini with 0.5 mm nozzle.

I designed and printed an LED holder in the form of a light ring.
It uses 3 LED's, 3 resistors, and gets it's power from the 5v used for the optical limit switches (which I removed after one day.)

Run the stl file through blender or similar, and then skeinforge with the "outside extruded first" box UNchecked in FILL and print. Ream the LED holes with a 5mm drill, install LED's, wire the LED's in parallel; with each resistor in series with the respective LED. Install the light ring on the extra length of the long 3mm screws, and plug it in.
Enjoy!

comments.text: Some of the weathering was to use a dremil tool to dent, cut, and make little marks on the original crisp hard edge print. After sanding away some of the 3D print texture as well, I used a thick primer. 2-3 coats of a good primer coat. Then once i was happy with the texture overall, I spray painted it silver. Do not use a chrome as this will be hard to paint over.  Next I used acrylic paint and a number of different painting techniques. You can start by dabbing paint on with a brush. Start with darker colors and move up to lighter ones. Use a number of different colors. Dark brown, Burnt Sienna, reds, oranges, yellows. Good weathering has a mixture of colors. I would dab on some color and then use a cloth to wipe some of it off. This allows some of the silver below to show through. You can also later use a sponge to apply some of the upper layers of paint that you do not plan on wiping away so much. A sponge with big holes in it provides a random pattern. Always be mindful to not get into patterns. Move randomly with the brush or sponge to break up any patterns. As a last step I used some watered down dark ink to feel like oil in the crevices. I save this for last because this type of wash can easily rub off. Once it is color set how you like it spray coat it with a matt varnish. Those are the basics. Let me know if you have more questions, and share your project =]

description.text:
This clip holds tighter to the Anki track and has a wide opening to easily guide the track into the clip. The clip is redesigned to hold the rails back further in order to give a little more track space and make it easier for vehicle to ride over the clip. The rails are a bit longer in order to have less space between them. I also added a straight rail.

Print three straight or outer rails per side of track. One inner rail per track. Two clips per rail is enough with the tighter clip hold. I've actually used four clips per three rails due to the rails being longer and clips holding tighter... thus the two inside clips can hold the edges of two rails.

Bonus: This tighter clip holds on to cardboard real good. The clip and rails can be used with a homemade cardboard track with other vehicles. Or, perhaps for other cardboard projects. The clip and rails also stand up on their own if you want to use them as a fence or something without being clipped to anything.

I printed on my Flashforge Creator Pro using layer height .3mm (fast). No supports needed if clip printed on its side. I used 25% infill and find that the clip holds tighter with infill.

description.text:
Where I put my Monoprice Maker Select v2.1 was kinda dark and I found myself moved my table lamp or even uses flashlight to look at the print bed while printing. Tried to search for a small table lamp that fit my shelf, but nothing really hit me. Then I came across Dracos' design http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1532795 which looks beautiful ! I do have couple reel of 3528 SMD 12V LED light lying around waiting for the next project so I start tinkering Dracos' design. His was meant for 5050 SMD, which is slightly wider strip than my 3528 SMD strip. So I modify all the necessary parts to my LED strip's width and print it out. Work perfectly.

Included a pic showing how many pieces of which STL file need to print.

Looking from the front of the printer, the wires of Top and Left set of lights ran through the left Z column, the Right set of lights ran through the right side, I loop the cables around Z motor and go underneath the Y axis frame and zip tie it to all to the existing wires which goes to the Power Supply and simply screw it down to the +ve and -ve on the power supply. Printer on, lights on, Printer off, lights off. oh yeah.

Now I can see everything clearly even with the room light is off.

Since I put the PSU on the left side of the printer and mount the filament spool on top of the PSU, and I got the Z brace mod installed, I found the filament was rubbing on the Z brace quite a bit. Hence I created the filament feed module. Well, it's there and work for me.

I found myself needing metric bits for work on my 3D printer and it's not easy to come by metric drill bits in my area so I ended up ordering some off Amazon. They came in a plastic bag so thought I make a holder to keep them organized. I only added .05mm to the original print and I ended up having to drill out the holes with some standard bits to get workable tolerances. I found those bits to generally be anywhere from .10mm to .30mm larger than their metric equivalents so I re-sized the bit holes on this design to be .25mm larger than the metric bit size. Depending on your printer, this should fit about right, but I would recommend printing the sample piece first and then scaling the print to the size you need for best fit.

description.text:
Hello!

This is TILTED ADAPTER for Nocuta (or other 40x40x10) fan AND matching Fan Covers!

This tilted adapter has 4 benefits:

  • Noctua Fan is REALLY quiet and reliable! You should upgrade!
  • Fan is pumping cooler air (instead of warm from the bed) as it's tilted upwards.
  • Less intake turbulence (no warping on this side of the bed)
  • Full Noctua fan cover compatible, to prevent sickness from Noctua natural colors... ;)

Full Noctua cover has advantage of hiding the entire fan and also allows mounting the fan via rubber pads which are squished together, making the fan quieter.

Front fan cover is just there for aesthetics and there are 2 versions - the round and the square one. It is matched to the noctua fan design.

I recommend printing covers in color, so that hexagons steps-out while making adapter in black. Choose the material that you like and you need. While PLA is fine for this parts, it may be better to use ABS or PETG if you are printing a lot of ABS...

I'm using four M3x20 screws for the fan (cover) and four M3x10* or M3x12 for mounting the adapter in place. For front fan cover I use two M3x25mm.

title: Parametrische Schnecke / Parametric Worm
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Parametrische Schnecke

Erzeugt eine zylindrische Schnecke (archimedische Spirale) nach DIN 3975.

Der Radius r des Wälzkreises der Schnecke bei gegebenem Modul m, Gangzahl z und Steigungswinkel γ ist

r = m·z·1⁄2sinγ

Format:

schnecke(modul, gangzahl, laenge, bohrung, eingriffswinkel, steigungswinkel, zusammen_gebaut)

Parameter:

modul = Höhe des Schneckenkopfes über dem Teilzylinder
gangzahl = Anzahl der Gänge (Zähne) der Schnecke
laenge = Länge der Schnecke
bohrung = Durchmesser der Mittelbohrung
eingriffswinkel = Eingriffswinkel, Standardwert = 20° gemäß DIN 867. Sollte nicht größer als 45° sein.
steigungswinkel = Steigungswinkel der Schnecke, entspricht 90°minus Schrägungswinkel. Positiver Steigungswinkel = rechtsdrehend.
zusammen_gebaut = Komponenten zusammengebaut (1) für Konstruktion oder auseinander (0) zum 3D-Druck

+++

Parametric Worm

Creates a cylidrical worm (archimedean spiral) following DIN 3975.

The worm's pitch circle r can be calculated out of its module m, number of threads z and lead angle γ:

r = m·z·1⁄2sinγ

Format:

schnecke(modul, gangzahl, laenge, bohrung, eingriffswinkel, steigungswinkel, zusammen_gebaut)

Parameters:

modul = height of the thread above the pitch circle
gangzahl = number of threads
laenge = length of the worm
bohrung = central bore diameter
eingriffswinkel = pressure angle, standard value = 20° according to DIN 867
steigungswinkel = lead angle of worm. Positive lead angle = clockwise thread rotation
zusammen_gebaut = assembled (1) or disassembled for printing (0)
